    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today with a focus on exploiting the porous matchups against Weiss and Buehler, making **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Josh Naylor** (74.15) our primary offensive anchors. **Mickey Moniak** benefits immensely from the high-upside matchup against Weiss and a dynamic platoon advantage that boosts his output to elite territory. Simultaneously, **Josh Naylor** finds himself in a prime spot; despite a neutral park, his efficiency is buoyed by a +19% SP skill modifier against Buehler, who is struggling with expected metrics. We are also leaning into the volume potential of **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (67.15), both of whom benefit from favorable park factors and high-leverage spots in the order against Montero and Leiter, respectively.\n\nWhile we are chasing efficiency, the stolen base scarcity in our 5x5 format keeps **Brice Turang** (65.73) and **Jose Caballero** (67.23) firmly in the starting lineup. **Brice Turang**\u2019s score is bolstered by an 86% stolen base efficiency rating against the slower delivery of Corbin, while **Jose Caballero** enjoys a significant +13% platoon edge against Suter. The most difficult decision rested on **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (58.46), who sits in a marginal tier; despite his speed, a negative platoon adjustment against Suter suppresses his ceiling just enough to make him the \"last man in,\" narrowly edging out bench options that remain inactive today. We must exercise caution with **James Wood** (53.92); though his leadoff spot adds value, the matchup against Ashcraft\u2014who holds a 62% efficiency in keeping runners at bay\u2014limits his stolen base upside, making him a riskier start than the rest of our core. Be mindful that **Luis Campusano** (41.89) remains at the absolute floor of our starting threshold; with a sub-optimal batting position and a tough matchup against Castillo, he is a primary candidate for replacement should we need to protect our limited game caps later in the week.",
